<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-06-18T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-06-18T15:00:00-05:00" n="112" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">701.6111/373: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate
                                    Peace</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-06-18T21:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">June 18,
                                        1919, 9 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:07
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>2635. Further referring to your 2294, June 13, 4 p.m.<note n="18" xml:id="d112fn18">Not printed.</note> President states:</p>
                        <p>“Of course, if <persName>Martens</persName> is a German subject and can
                            be legitimately deported, I have no objection because such grounds would
                            be abundant, but I hope the evidence is in fact complete.”</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">American Mission</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>